# Cross-Cutting Engineering Standards

These apply to **every** Turboplan project unless the user explicitly overrides
them for a specific product. Bootstrap must surface conflicts as concerns.

## 1. Language defaults (stack preference)

### Backend / server / CLI / daemons

- **Prefer Go** for all backend, server, CLI, and daemon work when the problem
  fits a systems/service shape.
- If there is a **strong** reason to use another language (ecosystem lock-in,
  mandated runtime, existing large codebase, client-only constraint), raise it
  as a **bootstrap concern** with a short rationale — do not silently pick it.
- For most greenfield backend applications, **Go is the default best choice**.

### Frontend / desktop

| Need | Prefer |
| ---- | ------ |
| Mostly static / content site | **Astro** |
| Complex application-style UI logic | **Vue** |
| Desktop app (native shell + web UI) | **Wails** (Go backend + web frontend) |

Do not invent a parallel frontend stack without stating why the default fails.

## 2. Tests (hard requirement)

- **Every new code path ships with tests** in the same task that introduces it
  (or an immediately preceding pure-test task if the plan splits that way).
- **Go:** use the standard `testing` package; prefer **table-driven** tests;
  cover success, important failures, and edge cases that would break callers.
- Other languages: follow that language’s idiomatic unit-test layout, still
  thorough enough to gate merges.
- No “tests later” for production code in `/task-2-execute` or `/task-3-complete`.

## 3. Linting and auto-fix (hard requirement)

- All product code must pass **language-specific lint / static analysis**.
- Prefer tools that **auto-fix** (formatters + fixable linters). Run auto-fix
  first; **fail the gate only** when remaining issues cannot be auto-cleaned.
- Wire lint into the same verify path as tests (Makefile target, `lefthook`, etc.).

## 4. Git + pre-commit (bootstrap acceptance)

Bootstrap is **not complete** until:

1. The project is a **git repository** (`git init` if none exists — do not
   re-init over an existing `.git` without asking).
2. Root **verify tooling** is present: `Makefile` with `verify`, stack lint
   config, and **`lefthook.yml`** (or approved equivalent). Seeds under
   `planning/` alone do **not** satisfy this — adapted copies must land at
   **repo root**.
3. A **pre-commit hook** runs **all tests and lints** (the project’s full verify
   suite). Prefer **[lefthook](https://github.com/evilmartians/lefthook)** over
   ad-hoc hook scripts; wire pre-commit → `make verify`.
4. Document how to install hooks (e.g. `make install-hooks` / `lefthook install`)
   in the hub Build & Run section.

See also §6 (execute/complete fail closed if this tooling is missing later).

## 5. Latest stable toolchain (bootstrap)

When bootstrapping (and when first introducing a language/tool in early tasks):

- Install **Go** and other baseline tools at the **latest stable** release (not
  beta/RC unless the user asks). Prefer the official installer / version manager
  the project already uses (`mise`, `asdf`, distro packages, or go.dev tarball).
- Add/upgrade language dependencies to **latest stable** compatible versions
  (`go get` / `go mod tidy` with current stables; Astro/Vue/Wails/Yarn at current
  stable tags — not `latest` tags that resolve to unstable majors unless verified).
- Record chosen versions in hub Build & Run / Architecture so execute agents
  match the baseline.
- If the environment cannot upgrade (locked CI image, policy), raise a
  **bootstrap concern** and document the pinned older version.

## 6. Execute / complete verification gate

`/task-2-execute` and `/task-3-complete` **must** run the full lint + test
(verify) suite as part of acceptance. Failures block INDEX `✅` and block the
close-out commit.

**Presence is mandatory (fail closed):** before treating verify as green, agents
must confirm a root `Makefile` with a `verify` target (lint+test[+build]), stack lint
config (e.g. `.golangci.yml` for Go), and `lefthook.yml` (or approved equivalent)
with pre-commit → that verify. If any are missing: **abort** — Status `Blocked`
on execute; no ✅ / commit / push on complete. Do **not** accept package tests
alone as a substitute for the full gate.

**Go Makefile (bootstrap):** include `lint`, `test`, `build`, multi-platform
`build-all`, and `verify` (= lint + test + build). Seeds:
`templates/seeds/verify/`.

## 7. Complete: push + manual test handoff

`/task-3-complete` by default **pushes** the completed branch to `origin`
(`git push -u origin HEAD`) after a successful commit.

- Opt out with **`--no-push`** on the skill invocation (local commit + next
  branch only).
- Never force-push. Never push secrets.
- Close-out output **must** include **Manual test** commands the human can run
  (e.g. start server + `curl` + what to look for). If nothing is runnable yet,
  write **`Nothing to test`** and explain why (e.g. library-only change, no
  binary, depends on later tunnel task).

